The world born of September 11th
NEW YORK – This week marks the 20th anniversary of the September 11, 2001, terrorist attacks in the United States.
On that day, 19 terrorists took control of four civilian airplanes, crashed two of the planes into the towers of the World Trade Center in New York, hit the Pentagon with a third, and then led to the crash of a fourth plane in Pennsylvania after several passengers physically prevented the terrorists from reaching their target, which many believe was the White House or another government building in Washington, DC.
All the air pirates were from the Middle East, and 15 of them were from Saudi Arabia.
All had been trained in Afghanistan, and four in American flight schools, as part of a planned, organized, and carried out operation by Al-Qaeda (the "base"), a terrorist group led by Osama bin Laden.
By the end of the day, 2,977 innocent men, women, and children had been killed, and more than 6,000 were injured.
Most were American, although citizens from more than a hundred other countries also lost their lives.
Many at the time feared that September 11th had ushered in an era defined by global terrorism.
Indeed, other attacks carried out by Al-Qaeda followed, including several bombings on Madrid trains in March 2004, and then the attack on London's public transportation system in July 2005.
Terrorists who pledged allegiance to the Islamic State (IS) also killed 32 people at Brussels Airport in March 2016, and carried out a series of smaller-scale attacks (often using vehicles to strike pedestrians).
Nevertheless, neither the United States nor any of its allies have ever suffered an attack of comparable magnitude to those of September 11th — which are in a class of their own.
It is therefore appropriate to ask: Beyond the immediate losses, what difference has September 11th made?
Has history changed, and if so, to what extent?
Many reasons explain why the terrorists have not been able to carry out other major attacks.
After the American invasion of Afghanistan, Al-Qaeda lost its sanctuary.
Almost all governments in the world have implemented control procedures making it more difficult for potential terrorists to access airports and airplanes.
States have significantly strengthened their intelligence, police, and military capabilities in order to minimize risks and counter threats.
They have also developed mutual cooperation, terrorism being one of the few areas in which often-disagreeing states are willing and ready to work together to a significant extent.
There is now also a broad consensus on what constitutes terrorism—the use of armed force by individuals and groups against civilians for political purposes—as well as a degree of support for the principle that governments cannot make a distinction between terrorists and those who provide them with sanctuary and support.
The era is over when individuals and groups willing to kill in the name of their cause were romanticized as freedom fighters.
It is not to claim that terrorism has ceased to take the lives of tens of thousands of people each year.
Nevertheless, almost all attacks occur in the Middle East, Africa, and South Asia within the context of ongoing conflicts (primarily in Iraq, Syria, Afghanistan, Libya, Somalia, Nigeria, Pakistan, and Yemen), as opposed to isolated attacks of the 9/11 type against major powers.
Terrorism is becoming increasingly localized and decentralized.
It is also resilient: the capture or elimination of a terrorist organization's leader does not necessarily mean the end of the group.
For example, Al-Qaeda survived the elimination of Bin Laden by American special forces in Pakistan, nearly ten years after the September 11th attacks.
It is therefore not surprising that terrorism persists, with no resolution of the problem in sight.
The possibility of a new September 11 cannot be ruled out either, although the U.S. government recently stated that the "most urgent terrorist threat" to the country exists domestically.
As formulated by the Provisional Irish Republican Army after its failed attempt to assassinate British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher in 1984, "Today, we have not been lucky, but remember that it only takes us to be lucky once."
"You will always need to have them."
The danger lies in the fact that one day, terrorists may get hold of nuclear material, or manage to manufacture and use a biological or chemical weapon, in which case terrorism could determine the era.
For now, that is not the case.
September 11th marked a historic turning point, with a profound impact on American foreign policy over the past 20 years.
Although the attacks did not lead to an era of global terrorism, they indeed gave rise to the so-called global war on terror, with major consequences for the behavior of the United States around the world, America's image in the eyes of the world, and the way many Americans eventually came to view their country's foreign policy.
The saga began in Afghanistan.
Shortly after the September 11 attacks, the United States offered the Taliban, who then controlled the Afghan government, a choice: hand over the Al-Qaeda leaders about to leave the country and guilty of having organized the September 11 attacks, or risk their rule.
After the Taliban refused to hand over Al-Qaeda leaders, American intelligence and military forces collaborated with a loosely organized confederation of Afghan tribes, called the Northern Alliance, to overthrow the Taliban.
The United States contributed to the formation of a successor government that took control of most of the country.
This control has, however, never been total or uncontested.
Many individuals loyal to the Taliban and Al-Qaeda have taken refuge in the neighboring Pakistan, where they have gradually regained strength and resumed their military operations against the government that replaced them.
On their part, the United States have not done enough to build an Afghan army, reduce corruption, and deprive the Taliban of sanctuary in Pakistan.
Instead, America strengthened its own presence and military operations in Afghanistan, becoming essentially a partner of the government in its civil war.
At its peak, the U.S. intervention in Afghanistan mobilized more than 100,000 American soldiers.
Over twenty years, the cost of operations amounts to more than 2,000 billion dollars, with over 2,300 American lives lost, and several tens of thousands among Afghans.
The effort was both excessive and insufficient.
The American presence deprived the Afghan government of much of its legitimacy and generated opposition to the United States, while the Taliban proved more persevering than America, which in 2020 had lost all will to fight in a conflict destined only to result in an indefinite stalemate.
The global war against terrorism also led the United States to enter a war in Iraq.
The question remains open as to whether President George W. Bush would have taken military action if September 11th had not occurred.
The attacks certainly reinforced his tendency to want to signal to the world that the United States were not, as President Richard Nixon had phrased during the Vietnam War, a "helpless and pitiable giant."
This led certain members of the administration (most notably Vice President Dick Cheney) to reject the risk of terrorists acquiring weapons of mass destruction, which Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein apparently possessed (although this ultimately turned out not to be the case), according to most of the protagonists.
Others aimed to spread democracy in Iraq and then throughout the entire Middle East, considering this approach not only feasible, but also likely to make the region much less prone to producing terrorists and supporting them.
La war in Iraq, launched in March 2003, did not unfold as the Bush administration, numerous members of Congress (including Joe Biden, then a senator), and world leaders who had approved it had wished or expected.
The United States were not prepared for the essential events to come.
The military victories initially achieved certainly allowed for the ousting of the government, but quickly gave way to widespread unrest as well as a violent civil war.
The decision to dissolve the Iraqi army and to exclude many Iraqis associated with the previous regime from government jobs has worsened an already chaotic situation.
More fundamentally, Iraq, like Afghanistan, has demonstrated the limits of what military force can achieve at a reasonable cost and within a reasonable timeframe.
In the end, the United States was forced to strengthen its military presence, bringing it to nearly 170,000 troops, in order to protect the besieged successor government in Baghdad.
A certain degree of stability has been achieved, but at a considerable cost.
The United States has spent at least as much in Iraq as in Afghanistan, but at a far heavier human toll: over 4,000 American soldiers killed, a significantly larger number wounded, and a rising rate of suicide among American military personnel (from both Iraq and Afghanistan).
This total excludes, moreover, deaths among private contractors and Iraqis, for whom estimates vary widely, but whose number certainly exceeds several hundred thousand.
The war in Iraq has also weakened the United States in other respects.
No evidence has ever proven Iraq's involvement in the September 11th attacks, and America's reputation suffered when the argument for military intervention without United Nations approval—aimed at eliminating Saddam's weapons of mass destruction—was revealed to be based on no solid foundation.
Images of American soldiers mistreating Iraqi prisoners have further tarnished the country's reputation.
Moreover, an Iraq at war with itself has become synonymous with an emerging Iran as the most powerful country in the region (or one of the two most powerful if Israel is considered).
Since the war, Iran has strengthened its influence over Iraq, Syria, Yemen, and Lebanon.
Iraq and Afghanistan have also proven to be two major strategic distractions.
While the United States became deeply involved in the Middle East and South Asia, regions lacking major present powers and economic dynamism, the geopolitical balance has shifted against the United States, both in Europe and East Asia, due to the emergence of a more aggressive Russia as well as a stronger and more assertive China.
The global war on terrorism could not and did not provide the United States with a compass for their foreign policy approach toward a renewed rivalry among great powers.
The wars conducted following September 11th have also had significant internal consequences for the United States.
They have shaken confidence in a country that had emerged from the Cold War with historically unprecedented preponderant power, and undermined the national unity that had surfaced immediately after the attacks.
The costs and failures associated with these wars have further fueled opposition to a major and lasting global role for the United States, giving rise to a new isolationist trend.
Similarly, this combative tendency, associated with the global financial crisis of 2007-2009 and its economic repercussions, has severely affected the confidence of Americans in the elites, thus fueling the rise of a populist sentiment that, among other consequences, contributed to Donald Trump's rise to power.
Today's America is more divided than ever internally, and increasingly less inclined to pursue this form of active foreign policy that characterized it since the end of World War II, which as a whole has largely benefited Americans as well as many others.
In retrospect, we can today view September 11th as a harbinger of what was to come: not so much the globalization of terrorism as the terrors of globalization.
The attacks conveyed the message that distance and borders mattered little in the global era.
Nothing remains local for very long anymore, whether it be terrorists born in the Middle East and trained in Afghanistan, or the effects of a global financial crisis that originated in poor American financial management.
We are currently all facing a pandemic virus that has killed several million people since its emergence in China in December 2019.
The fires, droughts, floods, storms, and heatwaves devastating many regions of the world are the consequence of climate change, itself a cumulative effect of human activity that releases unsustainable amounts of heat-trapping greenhouse gases into the atmosphere.
The era initiated by recent events comes to a close, marking the 20th anniversary of the American intervention in the country.
Twenty years ago, the Taliban were quickly ousted from power; in recent weeks, they have regained it just as easily.
It is too early to know whether the Taliban will resume their old habits by once again becoming a sanctuary for terrorism, and whether terrorists around the world will take pride in their victory over America and its allies.
What we do know, on the other hand, is that terrorism remains a characteristic of our world.
It will not define the future, but will remain one of the visible aspects of a globalization that already determines it.
